# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: game-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The **client–server model** is a form of messaging pattern in a distributed application structure that partitions tasks or workloads between the providers of a resource or service, called servers, and service requesters, called clients.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Often clients and servers communicate over a computer network on separate hardware, but both client and server may be on the same device.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A server host runs one or more server programs, which share their resources with clients.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A client usually does not share its computing resources, but it requests content or service from a server and may share its own content as part of the request.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Clients, therefore, initiate communication sessions with servers, which await incoming requests.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Examples of computer applications that use the client–server model are email, network printing, and the World Wide Web.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The server component provides a function or service to one or many clients, which initiate requests for such services.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Servers are classified by the services they provide.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] For example, a web server serves web pages and a file server serves computer files.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A shared resource may be any of the server computer's software and electronic components, from programs and data to processors and storage devices.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The sharing of resources of a server constitutes a *service*.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Whether a computer is a client, a server, or both, is determined by the nature of the application that requires the service functions.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] For example, a single computer can run a web server and file server software at the same time to serve different data to clients making different kinds of requests.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The client software can also communicate with server software within the same computer.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Communication between servers, such as to synchronize data, is sometimes called *inter-server* or *server-to-server* communication.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Generally, a service is an abstraction of computer resources and a client does not have to be concerned with how the server performs while fulfilling the request and delivering the response.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The client only has to understand the response based on the relevant application protocol, i.e. the content and the formatting of the data for the requested service.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Clients and servers exchange messages in a request–response messaging pattern.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The client sends a request, and the server returns a response.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This exchange of messages is an example of inter-process communication.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] To communicate, the computers must have a common language, and they must follow rules so that both the client and the server know what to expect.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The language and rules of communication are defined in a communications protocol.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] All protocols operate in the application layer.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The application layer protocol defines the basic patterns of the dialogue.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] To formalize the data exchange even further, the server may implement an application programming interface (API).
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The API is an abstraction layer for accessing a service.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] By restricting communication to a specific content format, it facilitates parsing.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] By abstracting access, it facilitates cross-platform data exchange.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A server may receive requests from many distinct clients in a short period.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A computer can only perform a limited number of tasks at any moment, and relies on a scheduling system to prioritize incoming requests from clients to accommodate them.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] To prevent abuse and maximize availability, the server software may limit the availability to clients.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Denial of service attacks are designed to exploit a server's obligation to process requests by overloading it with excessive request rates.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Encryption should be applied if sensitive information is to be communicated between the client and the server.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] When a bank customer accesses online banking services with a web browser (the client), the client initiates a request to the bank's web server.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The customer's login credentials are compared against a database, and the webserver accesses that database server as a client.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] An application server interprets the returned data by applying the bank's business logic and provides the output to the webserver.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Finally, the webserver returns the result to the client web browser for display.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In each step of this sequence of client–server message exchanges, a computer processes a request and returns data.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This is the request-response messaging pattern.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] When all the requests are met, the sequence is complete.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This example illustrates a design pattern applicable to the client–server model: separation of concerns.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Server-side refers to programs and operations that run on the server.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This is in contrast to client-side programs and operations which run on the client.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] "Server-side software" refers to a computer application, such as a web server, that runs on remote server hardware, reachable from a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Operations may be performed server-side because they require access to information or functionality that is not available on the client, or because performing such operations on the client side would be slow, unreliable, or insecure.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Client and server programs may be commonly available ones such as free or commercial web servers and web browsers, communicating with each other using standardized protocols.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Or, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Server-side operations include both those that are carried out in response to client requests, and non-client-oriented operations such as maintenance tasks.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In a computer security context, server-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on a server computer system, rather than on the client side, or in between the two.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] For example, an attacker might exploit an SQL injection vulnerability in a web application in order to maliciously change or gain unauthorized access to data in the server's database.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might break into a server system using vulnerabilities in the underlying operating system and then be able to access database and other files in the same manner as authorized administrators of the server.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In the case of an Internet-dependent user application like Google Earth, while querying and display of map data takes place on the client side, the server is responsible for permanent storage of map data, resolving user queries into map data to be returned to the client, etc.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Web applications and services can be implemented in almost any language, as long as they can return data to standards-based web browsers (possibly via intermediary programs) in formats which they can use.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Client-side refers to operations that are performed by the client in a computer network.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Typically, a client is a computer application, such as a web browser, that runs on a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device, and connects to a server as necessary.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Additionally, if operations can be performed by the client, without sending data over the network, they may take less time, use less bandwidth, and incur a lesser security risk.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example according to standard protocols such as HTTP or FTP, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (e.g. most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both HTTP and FTP).
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be termed client-side operations.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In a computer security context, client-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on the client / user's computer system, rather than on the server side, or in between the two.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] As an example, if a server contained an encrypted file or message which could only be decrypted using a key housed on the user's computer system, a client-side attack would normally be an attacker's only opportunity to gain access to the decrypted contents.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] For instance, the attacker might cause malware to be installed on the client system, allowing the attacker to view the user's screen, record the user's keystrokes, and steal copies of the user's encryption keys, etc.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might employ cross-site scripting vulnerabilities to execute malicious code on the client's system without needing to install any permanently resident malware.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Distributed computing projects such as SETI@home and the Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search, as well as Internet-dependent applications like Google Earth, rely primarily on client-side operations.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] They initiate a connection with the server (either in response to a user query, as with Google Earth, or in an automated fashion, as with SETI@home), and request some data.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The server selects a data set (a server-side operation) and sends it back to the client.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The client then analyzes the data (a client-side operation), and, when the analysis is complete, displays it to the user (as with Google Earth) and/or transmits the results of calculations back to the server (as with SETI@home).
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] An early form of client–server architecture is remote job entry, dating at least to OS/360 (announced 1964), where the request was to run a job, and the response was the output.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] While formulating the client–server model in the 1960s and 1970s, computer scientists building ARPANET (at the Stanford Research Institute) used the terms *server-host* (or *serving host*) and *user-host* (or *using-host*), and these appear in the early documents RFC 5 and RFC 4.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This usage was continued at Xerox PARC in the mid-1970s.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] One context in which researchers used these terms was in the design of a computer network programming language called Decode-Encode Language (DEL).
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The purpose of this language was to accept commands from one computer (the user-host), which would return status reports to the user as it encoded the commands in network packets.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Another DEL-capable computer, the server-host, received the packets, decoded them, and returned formatted data to the user-host.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A DEL program on the user-host received the results to present to the user.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Development of DEL was just beginning in 1969, the year that the United States Department of Defense established ARPANET (predecessor of Internet).
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] An early use of the word *client* occurs in "Separating Data from Function in a Distributed File System", a 1978 paper by Xerox PARC computer scientists Howard Sturgis, James Mitchell, and Jay Israel.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The authors are careful to define the term for readers, and explain that they use it to distinguish between the user and the user's network node (the client).
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] By 1992, the word *server* had entered into general parlance.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The client-server model does not dictate that server-hosts must have more resources than client-hosts.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Rather, it enables any general-purpose computer to extend its capabilities by using the shared resources of other hosts.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Centralized computing, however, specifically allocates a large number of resources to a small number of computers.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The more computation is offloaded from client-hosts to the central computers, the simpler the client-hosts can be.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] It relies heavily on network resources (servers and infrastructure) for computation and storage.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] A diskless node loads even its operating system from the network, and a computer terminal has no operating system at all; it is only an input/output interface to the server.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In contrast, a rich client, such as a personal computer, has many resources and does not rely on a server for essential functions.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] As microcomputers decreased in price and increased in power from the 1980s to the late 1990s, many organizations transitioned computation from centralized servers, such as mainframes and minicomputers, to rich clients.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This afforded greater, more individualized dominion over computer resources, but complicated information technology management.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] During the 2000s, web applications matured enough to rival application software developed for a specific microarchitecture.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] This maturation, more affordable mass storage, and the advent of service-oriented architecture were among the factors that gave rise to the cloud computing trend of the 2010s.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In addition to the client-server model, distributed computing applications often use the peer-to-peer (P2P) application architecture.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In the client-server model, the server is often designed to operate as a centralized system that serves many clients.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] The computing power, memory and storage requirements of a server must be scaled appropriately to the expected workload.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Load-balancing and failover systems are often employed to scale the server beyond a single physical machine.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Load balancing is defined as the methodical and efficient distribution of network or application traffic across multiple servers in a server farm.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Each load balancer sits between client devices and backend servers, receiving and then distributing incoming requests to any available server capable of fulfilling them.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In a peer-to-peer network, two or more computers (*peers*) pool their resources and communicate in a decentralized system.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Peers are coequal, or equipotent nodes in a non-hierarchical network.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Unlike clients in a client-server or client-queue-client network, peers communicate with each other directly.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] In peer-to-peer networking, an algorithm in the peer-to-peer communications protocol balances load, and even peers with modest resources can help to share the load.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] If a node becomes unavailable, its shared resources remain available as long as other peers offer it.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Ideally, a peer does not need to achieve high availability because other, redundant peers make up for any resource downtime; as the availability and load capacity of peers change, the protocol reroutes requests.
[src:game-networking/client-server-model] Both client-server and master-slave are regarded as sub-categories of distributed peer-to-peer systems.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Due to multiplayer games allowing players to interact with other individuals, they provide an element of social communication absent from single-player games.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The history of multiplayer video games extends over several decades, tracing back to the emergence of electronic gaming in the mid-20th century.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] One of the earliest instances of multiplayer interaction was witnessed with the development of *Spacewar!* in 1962 for the DEC PDP-1 computer by Steve Russell and colleagues at the MIT.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, multiplayer gaming gained momentum within the arcade scene with classics like *Pong* and *Tank*.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The transition to home gaming consoles in the 1980s further popularized multiplayer gaming.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Titles like *Super Mario Bros.* for the NES and *Golden Axe* for the Sega Genesis introduced cooperative and competitive gameplay.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Additionally, LAN gaming emerged in the late 1980s, enabling players to connect multiple computers for multiplayer gameplay, popularized by titles like *Doom* and *Warcraft: Orcs & Humans*.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Players can also play together in the same room using splitscreen.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Some of the earliest video games were two-player games, including early sports games (such as 1958's *Tennis For Two* and 1972's *Pong*), early shooter games such as *Spacewar!* (1962) and early racing video games such as *Astro Race* (1973).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The first examples of multiplayer real-time games were developed on the PLATO system about 1973.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Multi-user games developed on this system included 1973's Empire and 1974's Spasim; the latter was an early first-person shooter.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Other early video games included turn-based multiplayer modes, popular in tabletop arcade machines.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] In such games, play is alternated at some point (often after the loss of a life).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] All players' scores are often displayed onscreen so players can see their relative standing.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Danielle Bunten Berry created some of the first multiplayer video games, such as her debut, *Wheeler Dealers* (1978) and her most notable work, *M.U.L.E.* (1983).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Kemeny wrote in 1972 that software running on the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System (DTSS) had recently gained the ability to support multiple simultaneous users, and that games were the first use of the functionality.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] DTSS's popular American football game, he said, now supported head-to-head play by two humans.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The university's computer system had hundreds of terminals, connected (via serial lines) through cluster PDP-11s for student, teacher, and staff access.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The games had a program running on each terminal (for each player), sharing a segment of shared memory (known as the "high segment" in the OS TOPS-10).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The games became popular, and the university often banned them because of their RAM use.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] STAR was based on 1974's single-user, turn-oriented BASIC program STAR, written by Michael O'Shaughnessy at UNH.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Wasserman and Stryker in 1980 described in *BYTE* how to network two Commodore PET computers with a cable.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Their article includes a type-in, two-player Hangman, and describes the authors' more-sophisticated *Flash Attack*.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] SuperSet Software's *Snipes* (1981) uses networking technology that would become Novell NetWare.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Digital Equipment Corporation distributed another multi-user version of *Star Trek*, Decwar, without real-time screen updating; it was widely distributed to universities with DECsystem-10s.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] In 1981 Cliff Zimmerman wrote an homage to *Star Trek* in MACRO-10 for DECsystem-10s and -20s using VT100-series graphics.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] "VTtrek" pitted four Federation players against four Klingons in a three-dimensional universe.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer gaming modes are known as "netplay".
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The first popular video-game title with a Local Area Network(LAN) version, 1991's Spectre for the Apple Macintosh, featured AppleTalk support for up to eight players.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Spectre's popularity was partially attributed to the display of a player's name above their cybertank.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] There followed 1993's Doom, whose first network version allowed four simultaneous players.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-email multiplayer games use email to communicate between computers.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Other turn-based variations not requiring players to be online simultaneously are Play-by-post gaming and Play-by-Internet.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Some online games are "massively multiplayer", with many players participating simultaneously.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Two massively multiplayer genres are MMORPG (such as *World of Warcraft* or *EverQuest*) and MMORTS.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] First-person shooters have become popular multiplayer games; *Battlefield 1942* and *Counter-Strike* have little (or no) single-player gameplay.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Developer and gaming site OMGPOP's library included multiplayer Flash games for the casual player until it was shut down in 2013.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Some networked multiplayer games, including MUDs and massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) such as RuneScape, omit a single-player mode.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The largest MMO in 2008 was *World of Warcraft*, with over 10 million registered players worldwide.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] *World of Warcraft* would hit its peak at 12 million players two years later in 2010, and in 2023 earned the Guinness World Record for best selling MMO video game.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This category of games requires multiple machines to connect via the Internet; before the Internet became popular, MUDs were played on time-sharing computer systems and games like *Doom* were played on a LAN.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Beginning with the Sega NetLink in 1996, Game.com in 1997 and Dreamcast in 2000, game consoles support network gaming over LANs and the Internet.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Many mobile phones and handheld consoles also offer wireless gaming with Bluetooth (or similar) technology.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] By the early 2010s online gaming had become a mainstay of console platforms such as Xbox and PlayStation.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] During the 2010s, as the number of Internet users increased, two new video game genres rapidly gained worldwide popularity – multiplayer online battle arena and battle royale game, both designed exclusively for multiplayer gameplay over the Internet.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Over time the number of people playing video games has increased.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] In 2020, the majority of households in the United States have an occupant that plays video games, and 65% of gamers play multiplayer games with others either online or in person.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] For some games, "multiplayer" implies that players are playing on the same gaming system or network.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This applies to all arcade games, but also to a number of console, and personal computer games too.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Turn-based games such as chess also lend themselves to single system single screen and even to a single controller.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Multiple types of games allow players to use local multiplayer.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The term "local co-op" or "couch co-op" refers to local multiplayer games played in a cooperative manner on the same system; these may use split-screen or some other display method.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Hot-seat games are typically turn-based games with only one controller or input set – such as a single keyboard/mouse on the system.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Players rotate using the input device to perform their turn such that each is taking a turn on the "hot-seat".
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Not all local multiplayer games are played on the same console or personal computer.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Some local multiplayer games are played over a LAN.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This involves multiple devices using one local network to play together.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer games on LAN eliminate common problems faced when playing online such as lag and anonymity.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Games played on a LAN network are the focus of LAN parties.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] While local co-op and LAN parties still take place, there has been a decrease in both due to an increasing number of players and games utilizing online multiplayer gaming.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Online multiplayer games connect players over a wide area network (a common example being the Internet).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Unlike local multiplayer, players playing online multiplayer are not restricted to the same local network.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This allows players to interact with others from a much greater distance.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Playing multiplayer online offers the benefits of distance, but it also comes with its own unique challenges.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Gamers refer to latency using the term "ping", after a utility which measures round-trip network communication delays (by the use of ICMP packets).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] A player on a DSL connection with a 50-ms ping can react faster than a modem user with a 350-ms average latency.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Other problems include packet loss and choke, which can prevent a player from "registering" their actions with a server.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] In first-person shooters, this problem appears when bullets hit the enemy without damage.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] The player's connection is not the only factor; some servers are slower than others.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] A server that is geographically closer to the player's connection will often provide a lower ping.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Data packets travel faster to a location that is closer to them.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] How far the device is from an internet connection (router) can also affect latency.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Asymmetrical multiplayer is a type of gameplay in which players can have significantly different roles or abilities from each other – enough to provide a significantly different experience of the game.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] A first-person shooter that adopts the asymmetrical multiplayer system is Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Giving players their own special operator changes every player's experience.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This puts an emphasis on players improvising their own game plan given the abilities their character has.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] In games with stronger elements of asymmetry, one player/team may have one gameplay experience (or be in softly asymmetric roles) while the other player or team play in a drastically different way, with different mechanics, a different type of objective, or both.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Examples of games with strong asymmetry include *Dead by Daylight*, *Evolve*, and *Left 4 Dead*.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Deathloop featured opt‑in asymmetric PvP and Elden Ring’s evolved Souls invasions at scale.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Depending on the game, objectives and story, the invading player(s) goals, roles, and own objectives will be different.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Asynchronous multiplayer is a form of multiplayer gameplay where players are not necessarily playing at the same time.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This form of multiplayer game has its origins in play-by-mail games, where players would send their moves through postal mail to a game master, who then would compile and send out results for the next turn.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-mail games transitioned to electronic form as play-by-email games.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Similar games were developed for bulletin board systems, such as *Trade Wars*, where the turn structure may not be as rigorous and allow players to take actions at any time in a persistence space alongside all other players, a concept known as sporadic play.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] These types of asynchronous multiplayer games waned with the widespread availability of the Internet which allowed players to play against each other simultaneously, but remains an option in many strategy-related games, such as the *Civilization* series.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Coordination of turns are subsequently managed by one computer or a centralized server.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Further, many mobile games are based on sporadic play and use social interactions with other players, lacking direct player versus player game modes but allowing players to influence other players' games, coordinated through central game servers, another facet of asynchronous play.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Online cheating (in gaming) usually refers to modifying the game experience to give one player an advantage over others, such as using an "aimbot" – a program which automatically locks the player's crosshairs onto a target – in shooting games.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] This is also known as "hacking" or "glitching" ("glitching" refers to using a glitch, or a mistake in the code of a game, whereas "hacking" is manipulating the code of a game).
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] Cheating in video games is often done via a third-party program that modifies the game's code at runtime to give one or more players an advantage.
[src:game-networking/multiplayer-video-game] In other situations, it is frequently done by changing the game's files to change the game's mechanics.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Players often blame "bad netcode" when they experience lag or reverse state transitions when synchronization between players is lost.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Although these events are sometimes caused by bugs, other networking-related causes include high latency between server and client, packet loss, or network congestion.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Depending on the game implementation, these issues can also be caused by non-network factors such as frame rendering time or inconsistent frame rate.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Netcode is often designed to mask networking irregularities and create a synchronous and smooth gamestate across multiple users.
[src:game-networking/netcode] There are two main resolutions to this conflict implemented in modern games: delay-based and rollback-based resolution.
[src:game-networking/netcode] The classic solution to this problem is the use of a delay-based netcode.
[src:game-networking/netcode] When the inputs of a remote player arrive late, the game delays the inputs of the local player accordingly to synchronize the two inputs and run them simultaneously.
[src:game-networking/netcode] This added delay can be disruptive for players (especially when latency is high), but overall the change is not very noticeable.
[src:game-networking/netcode] However, these delays can be inconsistent due to sudden fluctuations in current latency.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Should the latency between players exceed an established buffer window for the remote player, the game must wait, causing the screens to "freeze".
[src:game-networking/netcode] This occurs because a delay-based netcode does not allow the simulation to continue until it receives the inputs from all the players in the frame in question.
[src:game-networking/netcode] This variable delay causes an inconsistent and unresponsive experience compared to offline play (or to a LAN game), and can negatively affect player performance in timing-sensitive and fast-paced genres such as fighting games.
[src:game-networking/netcode] An alternative system to the previous netcode is rollback netcode.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Some games utilize a hybrid solution in order to disguise these "jumps" (which can become problematic as latency between players grows, as there is less and less time to react to other players' actions) with a fixed input delay and then rollback being used.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Rollback is quite effective at concealing lag spikes or other issues related to inconsistencies in the users' connections, as predictions are often correct and players do not even notice.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Nevertheless, this system can be troublesome whenever a client's game slows down (usually due to overheating), since rift problems can be caused leading to an exchange of tickets between machines at unequal rates.
[src:game-networking/netcode] This generates visual glitches that interrupt the gameplay of those players that receive inputs at a slower pace, while the player whose game is slowed down will have an advantage over the rest by receiving inputs from others at a normal rate (this is known as one-sided rollback).
[src:game-networking/netcode] There is a popular MIT-licensed library named GGPO designed to help implement rollback networking to games (mainly fighting games).
[src:game-networking/netcode] Latency is unavoidable in online games, and the quality of the player's experience is strictly tied to this (the more latency there is between players, the greater the feeling that the game is not responsive to their inputs).
[src:game-networking/netcode] The latency of the players' network (which is largely out of a game's control) is not the only factor in question, but also the latency inherent in the way the game simulations are run.
[src:game-networking/netcode] There are several lag compensation methods used to disguise or cope with latency (especially with high latency values).
[src:game-networking/netcode] A single update of a game simulation is known as a tick.
[src:game-networking/netcode] The rate at which the simulation is run on a server is often referred to as the server's tickrate; this is essentially the server equivalent of a client's frame rate, absent any rendering system.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Tickrate is limited by the length of time it takes to run the simulation, and is often intentionally limited further to reduce instability introduced by a fluctuating tickrate, and to reduce CPU and data transmission costs.
[src:game-networking/netcode] A lower tickrate increases latency in the synchronization of the game simulation between the server and clients.
[src:game-networking/netcode] A lower tickrate also naturally reduces the precision of the simulation, which itself might cause problems if taken too far, or if the client and server simulations are running at significantly different rates.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Because of limitations in the amount of available bandwidth and the CPU time that's taken by network communication, some games prioritize certain vital communications while limiting the frequency and priority of less important information.
[src:game-networking/netcode] As with tickrate, this effectively increases synchronization latency.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Game engines may limit the number of times that updates (of a simulation) are sent to a particular client and/or particular objects in the game's world in addition to reducing the precision of some values sent over the network to help with bandwidth use.
[src:game-networking/netcode] This lack of precision may in some instances be noticeable.
[src:game-networking/netcode] Various simulation synchronization errors between machines can also fall under the "netcode issues" blanket.
[src:game-networking/netcode] These may include bugs which cause the simulation to proceed differently on one machine than on another, or which cause some things to not be communicated when the user perceives that they ought to be.
[src:game-networking/netcode] A game's choice of transport layer protocol (and its management and coding) can also affect perceived networking issues.
[src:game-networking/netcode] If a game uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), there will be increased latency between players.
[src:game-networking/netcode] This protocol is based on the connection between two machines, in which they can exchange data and read it.
[src:game-networking/netcode] These types of connections are very reliable, stable, ordered and easy to implement.
[src:game-networking/netcode] This type of protocol also tends to respond very slowly whenever they lose a packet, or when packets arrive in an incorrect order or duplicated, which can be very detrimental to a real-time online game (this protocol was not designed for this type of software).
[src:game-networking/netcode] If the game instead uses a User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the connection between machines will be very fast, because instead of establishing a connection between them the data will be sent and received directly.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] In telecommunications, the specification of a network architecture may also include a detailed description of products and services delivered via a communications network, as well as detailed rate and billing structures under which services are compensated.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] The network architecture of the Internet is predominantly expressed by its use of the Internet protocol suite, rather than a specific model for interconnecting networks or nodes in the network, or the usage of specific types of hardware links.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] The Open Systems Interconnection model (OSI model) defines and codifies the concept of layered network architecture.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] Abstraction layers are used to subdivide a communications system further into smaller manageable parts.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] A layer is a collection of similar functions that provide services to the layer above it and receives services from the layer below it.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] On each layer, an instance provides services to the instances at the layer above and requests services from the layer below.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] In distributed computing, the *network architecture* often describes the structure and classification of a distributed application architecture, as the participating nodes in a distributed application are often referred to as a *network*.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] For example, the applications architecture of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) has been termed the Intelligent Network.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] There are a number of specific classifications but all lie on a continuum between the dumb network (e.g. the Internet) and the intelligent network (e.g. the PSTN).
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] A popular example of such usage of the term in distributed applications, as well as permanent virtual circuits, is the organization of nodes in peer-to-peer (P2P) services and networks.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] P2P networks usually implement overlay networks running over an underlying physical or logical network.
[src:game-networking/network-architecture] These overlay networks may implement certain organizational structures of the nodes according to several distinct models, the network architecture of the system.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The **Transmission Control Protocol** (**TCP**) is one of the main protocols of the Internet protocol suite, providing reliable, ordered, and error-checked delivery of a stream of octets (bytes) between applications running on hosts communicating via an IP network.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] It originated in the initial network implementation in which it complemented the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Therefore, the entire suite is commonly referred to as TCP/IP.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Major internet applications such as the World Wide Web, email, remote administration, file transfer and streaming media rely on TCP, which is part of the transport layer of the TCP/IP suite.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Today, TCP remains a core protocol for most Internet communication, ensuring reliable data transfer across diverse networks.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP is connection-oriented, meaning that sender and receiver first need to establish a connection based on agreed parameters; they do this through a three-way handshake procedure.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The server must be listening (passive open) for connection requests from clients before a connection is established.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The three-way handshake (active open), retransmission, and error detection add to reliability but lengthen latency.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Applications that do not require reliable data stream service may use the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) instead, which provides a connectionless datagram service that prioritizes time over reliability.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP employs network congestion avoidance.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] However, there are vulnerabilities in TCP, including denial of service, connection hijacking, TCP veto, and reset attack.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In May 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn described an internetworking protocol for sharing resources using packet switching among network nodes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The authors had been working with Gérard Le Lann to incorporate concepts from the French CYCLADES project into the new network.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The specification of the resulting protocol, RFC 675 (*Specification of Internet Transmission Control Program*), was written by Vint Cerf, Yogen Dalal, and Carl Sunshine, and published in December 1974.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] It contains the first attested use of the term *internet*, as a shorthand for *internetwork*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The Transmission Control Program incorporated both connection-oriented links and datagram services between hosts.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In version 4, the monolithic Transmission Control Program was divided into a modular architecture consisting of the *Transmission Control Protocol* and the *Internet Protocol*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This resulted in a networking model that became known informally as *TCP/IP*, although formally it was variously referred to as the *DoD internet architecture model* (*DoD model* for short) or *DARPA model*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Later, it became part of, and synonymous with, the *Internet Protocol Suite*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP continues to evolve, with incremental updates and best practices formalized in RFCs such as RFC 9293 (2022).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP was standardized in January 1980 as RFC 761.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In 2004, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn received the Turing Award for their foundational work on TCP/IP.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The Transmission Control Protocol provides a communication service at an intermediate level between an application program and the Internet Protocol.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] It provides host-to-host connectivity at the transport layer of the Internet model.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An application does not need to know the particular mechanisms for sending data via a link to another host, such as the required IP fragmentation to accommodate the maximum transmission unit of the transmission medium.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] At the transport layer, TCP handles all handshaking and transmission details and presents an abstraction of the network connection to the application typically through a network socket interface.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] At the lower levels of the protocol stack, due to network congestion, traffic load balancing, or unpredictable network behavior, IP packets may be lost, duplicated, or delivered out of order.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP detects these problems, requests re-transmission of lost data, rearranges out-of-order data and even helps minimize network congestion to reduce the occurrence of the other problems.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If the data still remains undelivered, the source is notified of this failure.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Once the TCP receiver has reassembled the sequence of octets originally transmitted, it passes them to the receiving application.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Thus, TCP abstracts the application's communication from the underlying networking details.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP is optimized for accurate delivery rather than timely delivery and can incur relatively long delays (on the order of seconds) while waiting for out-of-order messages or re-transmissions of lost messages.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Therefore, it is not particularly suitable for real-time applications such as voice over IP.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For such applications, protocols like the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) operating over the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) are usually recommended instead.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP is a reliable byte stream delivery service that guarantees that all bytes received will be identical and in the same order as those sent.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Since packet transfer by many networks is not reliable, TCP achieves this using a technique known as *positive acknowledgment with re-transmission*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This requires the receiver to respond with an acknowledgment message as it receives the data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sender keeps a record of each packet it sends and maintains a timer from when the packet was sent.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sender re-transmits a packet if the timer expires before receiving the acknowledgment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The timer is needed in case a packet gets lost or corrupted.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] While IP handles actual delivery of the data, TCP keeps track of *segments* – the individual units of data transmission that a message is divided into for efficient routing through the network.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For example, when an HTML file is sent from a web server, the TCP software layer of that server divides the file into segments and forwards them individually to the internet layer in the network stack.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The internet layer software encapsulates each TCP segment into an IP packet by adding a header that includes (among other data) the destination IP address.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When the client program on the destination computer receives them, the TCP software in the transport layer re-assembles the segments and ensures they are correctly ordered and error-free as it streams the file contents to the receiving application.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Transmission Control Protocol accepts data from a data stream, divides it into chunks, and adds a TCP header creating a TCP segment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The TCP segment is then encapsulated into an Internet Protocol (IP) datagram, and exchanged with peers.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A TCP segment consists of a segment *header* and a *data* section.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The segment header contains 10 mandatory fields, and an optional extension field (*Options*, octets 20 through 56 in table).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The data section follows the header and is the payload data carried for the application.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The length of the data section is not specified in the segment header; it can be calculated by subtracting the combined length of the segment header and IP header from the total IP datagram length specified in the IP header.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] (Options) If present, Data Offset will be greater than 5.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Padded with zeroes to a multiple of 32 bits, since Data Offset counts words of 4 octets.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If the ACK flag is set then the value of this field is the next sequence number that the sender of the ACK is expecting.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This acknowledges receipt of all prior bytes (if any).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The first ACK sent by each end acknowledges the other end's initial sequence number itself, but no data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The minimum size header is 5 words and the maximum is 15 words thus giving the minimum size of 20 bytes and maximum of 60 bytes, allowing for up to 40 bytes of options in the header.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This field gets its name from the fact that it is also the offset from the start of the TCP segment to the actual data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For future use and should be set to zero; senders should not set these and receivers should ignore them if set, in the absence of further specification and implementation.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] ECN-nonce never gained widespread use and the RFC was moved to Historic status.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Contains 8 1-bit flags (control bits) as follows.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] , a set flag is indicated with the character in parentheses.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Congestion window reduced (CWR) flag is set by the sending host to indicate that it received a TCP segment with the ECE flag set and had responded in congestion control mechanism.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] ECN-Echo has a dual role, depending on the value of the SYN flag.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Indicates that the Urgent pointer field is significant.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Indicates that the Acknowledgment field is significant.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] All packets after the initial SYN packet sent by the client should have this flag set.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Asks to push the buffered data onto the wire (i.e. send) on the sender end and to the receiving application at the receiver end.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Only the first packet sent from each end should have this flag set.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Some other flags and fields change meaning based on this flag, and some are only valid when it is set, and others when it is clear.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] that the sender of this segment is currently willing to receive.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] field is used for error-checking of the TCP header, the payload and an IP pseudo-header.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] for the TCP protocol (6) and the length of the TCP headers and payload (in bytes).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If the URG flag is set, then this 16-bit field is an offset from the sequence number indicating the last urgent data byte.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The TCP header padding is used to ensure that the TCP header ends, and data begins, on a 32-bit boundary.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Options have up to three fields: Option-Kind (1 byte), Option-Length (1 byte), Option-Data (variable).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The Option-Kind field indicates the type of option and is the only field that is not optional.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Depending on Option-Kind value, the next two fields may be set.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Option-Length indicates the total length of the option, and Option-Data contains data associated with the option, if applicable.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For example, an Option-Kind byte of 1 indicates that this is a no operation option used only for padding, and does not have an Option-Length or Option-Data fields following it.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An Option-Kind byte of 0 marks the end of options, and is also only one byte.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An Option-Kind byte of 2 is used to indicate Maximum Segment Size option, and will be followed by an Option-Length byte specifying the length of the MSS field.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Option-Length is the total length of the given options field, including Option-Kind and Option-Length fields.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] So while the MSS value is typically expressed in two bytes, Option-Length will be 4.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Option-Kind and standard lengths given as (Option-Kind, Option-Length).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The remaining Option-Kind values are historical, obsolete, experimental, not yet standardized, or unassigned.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP protocol operations may be divided into three phases.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] *Connection establishment* is a multi-step handshake process that establishes a connection before entering the *data transfer* phase.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] After data transfer is completed, the *connection termination* closes the connection and releases all allocated resources.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A TCP connection is managed by an operating system through a resource that represents the local end-point for communications, the *Internet socket*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Before a client attempts to connect with a server, the server must first bind to and listen at a port to open it up for connections: this is called a passive open.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] **SYN-ACK**: In response, the server replies with a SYN-ACK.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The acknowledgment number is set to one more than the received sequence number i.e. x+1, and the sequence number that the server chooses for the packet is another random number, y.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] **ACK**: Finally, the client sends an ACK back to the server.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sequence number is set to the received acknowledgment value i.e. x+1, and the acknowledgment number is set to one more than the received sequence number i.e. y+1.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Steps 1 and 2 establish and acknowledge the sequence number for one direction (client to server).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Steps 2 and 3 establish and acknowledge the sequence number for the other direction (server to client).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Following the completion of these steps, both the client and server have received acknowledgments and a full-duplex communication is established.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The connection termination phase uses a four-way handshake, with each side of the connection terminating independently.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When an endpoint wishes to stop its half of the connection, it transmits a FIN packet, which the other end acknowledges with an ACK.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Therefore, a typical tear-down requires a pair of FIN and ACK segments from each TCP endpoint.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The time duration is implementation-dependent, but some common values are 30 seconds, 1 minute, and 2 minutes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] After the timeout, the client enters the CLOSED state and the local port becomes available for new connections.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] It is also possible to terminate the connection by a 3-way handshake, when host A sends a FIN and host B replies with a FIN & ACK (combining two steps into one) and host A replies with an ACK.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Some operating systems, such as Linux implement a half-duplex close sequence.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If the host actively closes a connection, while still having unread incoming data available, the host sends the signal RST (losing any received data) instead of FIN.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This assures that a TCP application is aware there was a data loss.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A connection can be in a half-open state, in which case one side has terminated the connection, but the other has not.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The side that has terminated can no longer send any data into the connection, but the other side can.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The terminating side should continue reading the data until the other side terminates as well.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Most implementations allocate an entry in a table that maps a session to a running operating system process.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Because TCP packets do not include a session identifier, both endpoints identify the session using the client's address and port.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Whenever a packet is received, the TCP implementation must perform a lookup on this table to find the destination process.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Each entry in the table is known as a Transmission Control Block or TCB.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] It contains information about the endpoints (IP and port), status of the connection, running data about the packets that are being exchanged and buffers for sending and receiving data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The number of sessions in the server side is limited only by memory and can grow as new connections arrive, but the client must allocate an ephemeral port before sending the first SYN to the server.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This port remains allocated during the whole conversation and effectively limits the number of outgoing connections from each of the client's IP addresses.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If an application fails to properly close unrequired connections, a client can run out of resources and become unable to establish new TCP connections, even from other applications.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Both endpoints must also allocate space for unacknowledged packets and received (but unread) data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP uses a *sequence number* to identify each byte of data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sequence number identifies the order of the bytes sent from each computer so that the data can be reconstructed in order, regardless of any out-of-order delivery that may occur.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sequence number of the first byte is chosen by the transmitter for the first packet, which is flagged SYN.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This number can be arbitrary, and should, in fact, be unpredictable to defend against TCP sequence prediction attacks.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Acknowledgments (ACKs) are sent with a sequence number by the receiver of data to tell the sender that data has been received to the specified byte.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] ACKs do not imply that the data has been delivered to the application, they merely signify that it is now the receiver's responsibility to deliver the data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Reliability is achieved by the sender detecting lost data and retransmitting it.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP uses two primary techniques to identify loss.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Retransmission timeout (RTO) and duplicate cumulative acknowledgments (DupAcks).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When a TCP segment is retransmitted, it retains the same sequence number as the original delivery attempt.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This conflation of delivery and logical data ordering means that, when acknowledgment is received after a retransmission, the sender cannot tell whether the original transmission or the retransmission is being acknowledged, the so-called *retransmission ambiguity*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP incurs complexity due to retransmission ambiguity.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If a single segment (say segment number 100) in a stream is lost, then the receiver cannot acknowledge packets above that segment number (100) because it uses cumulative ACKs.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Hence the receiver acknowledges packet 99 again on the receipt of another data packet.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This duplicate acknowledgement is used as a signal for packet loss.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] That is, if the sender receives three duplicate acknowledgments, it retransmits the last unacknowledged packet.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A threshold of three is used because the network may reorder segments causing duplicate acknowledgements.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This threshold has been demonstrated to avoid spurious retransmissions due to reordering.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Some TCP implementations use selective acknowledgements (SACKs) to provide explicit feedback about the segments that have been received.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This greatly improves TCP's ability to retransmit the right segments.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Retransmission ambiguity can cause spurious fast retransmissions and congestion avoidance if there is reordering beyond the duplicate acknowledgment threshold.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In the last two decades more packet reordering has been observed over the Internet which led TCP implementations, such as the one in the Linux Kernel to adopt heuristic methods to scale the duplicate acknowledgment threshold.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Recently, there have been efforts to completely phase out duplicate-ACK-based fast-retransmissions and replace them with timer based ones.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] (Not to be confused with the classic RTO discussed below).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The time based loss detection algorithm called Recent Acknowledgment (RACK) has been adopted as the default algorithm in Linux and Windows.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When a sender transmits a segment, it initializes a timer with a conservative estimate of the arrival time of the acknowledgment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The segment is retransmitted if the timer expires, with a new timeout threshold of twice the previous value, resulting in exponential backoff behavior.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Typically, the initial timer value is smoothed RTT + max(*G*, 4 × RTT variation), where G is the clock granularity.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This guards against excessive transmission traffic due to faulty or malicious actors, such as man-in-the-middle denial of service attackers.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Accurate RTT estimates are important for loss recovery, as it allows a sender to assume an unacknowledged packet to be lost after sufficient time elapses (i.e., determining the RTO time).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Retransmission ambiguity can lead a sender's estimate of RTT to be imprecise.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In an environment with variable RTTs, spurious timeouts can occur: if the RTT is under-estimated, then the RTO fires and triggers a needless retransmit and slow-start.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] RFC 6298 specifies that implementations must not use retransmitted segments when estimating RTT.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Karn's algorithm ensures that a good RTT estimate will be produced—eventually—by waiting until there is an unambiguous acknowledgment before adjusting the RTO.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] After spurious retransmissions, however, it may take significant time before such an unambiguous acknowledgment arrives, degrading performance in the interim.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP timestamps also resolve the retransmission ambiguity problem in setting the RTO, though they do not necessarily improve the RTT estimate.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Sequence numbers allow receivers to discard duplicate packets and properly sequence out-of-order packets.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Acknowledgments allow senders to determine when to retransmit lost packets.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] To assure correctness a checksum field is included; see § Checksum computation for details.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The TCP checksum is a weak check by modern standards and is normally paired with a CRC integrity check at layer 2, below both TCP and IP, such as is used in PPP or the Ethernet frame.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] However, introduction of errors in packets between CRC-protected hops is common and the 16-bit TCP checksum catches most of these.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP uses an end-to-end flow control protocol to avoid having the sender send data too fast for the TCP receiver to receive and process it reliably.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Having a mechanism for flow control is essential in an environment where machines of diverse network speeds communicate.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For example, if a PC sends data to a smartphone that is slowly processing received data, the smartphone must be able to regulate the data flow so as not to be overwhelmed.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP uses a sliding window flow control protocol.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In each TCP segment, the receiver specifies in the *receive window* field the amount of additionally received data (in bytes) that it is willing to buffer for the connection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sending host can send only up to that amount of data before it must wait for an acknowledgment and receive window update from the receiving host.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When a receiver advertises a window size of 0, the sender stops sending data and starts its *persist timer*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The persist timer is used to protect TCP from a deadlock situation that could arise if a subsequent window size update from the receiver is lost, and the sender cannot send more data until receiving a new window size update from the receiver.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When the persist timer expires, the TCP sender attempts recovery by sending a small packet so that the receiver responds by sending another acknowledgment containing the new window size.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If a receiver is processing incoming data in small increments, it may repeatedly advertise a small receive window.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This is referred to as the silly window syndrome, since it is inefficient to send only a few bytes of data in a TCP segment, given the relatively large overhead of the TCP header.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The final main aspect of TCP is congestion control.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP uses a number of mechanisms to achieve high performance and avoid congestive collapse, a gridlock situation where network performance is severely degraded.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] These mechanisms control the rate of data entering the network, keeping the data flow below a rate that would trigger collapse.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] They also yield an approximately max-min fair allocation between flows.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Acknowledgments for data sent, or the lack of acknowledgments, are used by senders to infer network conditions between the TCP sender and receiver.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Coupled with timers, TCP senders and receivers can alter the behavior of the flow of data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This is more generally referred to as congestion control or congestion avoidance.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Modern implementations of TCP contain four intertwined algorithms: slow start, congestion avoidance, fast retransmit, and fast recovery.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In addition, senders employ a *retransmission timeout* (RTO) that is based on the estimated round-trip time (RTT) between the sender and receiver, as well as the variance in this round-trip time.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] There are subtleties in the estimation of RTT.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For example, senders must be careful when calculating RTT samples for retransmitted packets; typically they use Karn's Algorithm or TCP timestamps.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] These individual RTT samples are then averaged over time to create a smoothed round trip time (SRTT) using Jacobson's algorithm.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This SRTT value is what is used as the round-trip time estimate.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Enhancing TCP to reliably handle loss, minimize errors, manage congestion and go fast in very high-speed environments are ongoing areas of research and standards development.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] As a result, there are a number of TCP congestion avoidance algorithm variations.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The maximum segment size (MSS) is the largest amount of data, specified in bytes, that TCP is willing to receive in a single segment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For best performance, the MSS should be set small enough to avoid IP fragmentation, which can lead to packet loss and excessive retransmissions.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] To accomplish this, typically the MSS is announced by each side using the MSS option when the TCP connection is established.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The option value is derived from the maximum transmission unit (MTU) size of the data link layer of the networks to which the sender and receiver are directly attached.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP senders can use path MTU discovery to infer the minimum MTU along the network path between the sender and receiver, and use this to dynamically adjust the MSS to avoid IP fragmentation within the network.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] MSS announcement may also be called *MSS negotiation* but, strictly speaking, the MSS is not *negotiated*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Two completely independent values of MSS are permitted for the two directions of data flow in a TCP connection, so there is no need to agree on a common MSS configuration for a bidirectional connection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Relying purely on the cumulative acknowledgment scheme employed by the original TCP can lead to inefficiencies when packets are lost.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For example, suppose bytes with sequence number 1,000 to 10,999 are sent in 10 different TCP segments of equal size, and the second segment (sequence numbers 2,000 to 2,999) is lost during transmission.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In a pure cumulative acknowledgment protocol, the receiver can only send a cumulative ACK value of 2,000 (the sequence number immediately following the last sequence number of the received data) and cannot say that it received bytes 3,000 to 10,999 successfully.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Thus the sender may then have to resend all data starting with sequence number 2,000.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In the example above, the receiver would send an ACK segment with a cumulative ACK value of 2,000 and a SACK option header with sequence numbers 3,000 and 11,000.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sender would accordingly retransmit only the second segment with sequence numbers 2,000 to 2,999.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A TCP sender may interpret an out-of-order segment delivery as a lost segment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] If it does so, the TCP sender will retransmit the segment previous to the out-of-order packet and slow its data delivery rate for that connection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The duplicate-SACK option, an extension to the SACK option that was defined in May 2000 in RFC 2883, solves this problem.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Once the TCP receiver detects a second duplicate packet, it sends a D-ACK to indicate that no segments were lost, allowing the TCP sender to reinstate the higher transmission rate.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The SACK option is not mandatory and comes into operation only if both parties support it.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This is negotiated when a connection is established.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] SACK uses a TCP header option (see § TCP segment structure for details).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The use of SACK has become widespread—all popular TCP stacks support it.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Selective acknowledgment is also used in Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Selective acknowledgements can be 'reneged', where the receiver unilaterally discards the selectively acknowledged data.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] RFC 2018 discouraged such behavior, but did not prohibit it to allow receivers the option of reneging if they, for example, ran out of buffer space.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The possibility of reneging leads to implementation complexity for both senders and receivers, and also imposes memory costs on the sender.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For more efficient use of high-bandwidth networks, a larger TCP window size may be used.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A 16-bit TCP window size field controls the flow of data and its value is limited to 65,535 bytes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Since the size field cannot be expanded beyond this limit, a scaling factor is used.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The TCP window scale option, as defined in RFC 1323, is an option used to increase the maximum window size to 1 gigabyte.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Scaling up to these larger window sizes is necessary for TCP tuning.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The window scale option is used only during the TCP 3-way handshake.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The window scale value represents the number of bits to left-shift the 16-bit window size field when interpreting it.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The window scale value can be set from 0 (no shift) to 14 for each direction independently.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Both sides must send the option in their SYN segments to enable window scaling in either direction.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Some routers and packet firewalls rewrite the window scaling factor during a transmission.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This causes sending and receiving sides to assume different TCP window sizes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The result is non-stable traffic that may be very slow.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The problem is visible on some sites behind a defective router.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP timestamps, defined in RFC 1323 in 1992, can help TCP determine in which order packets were sent.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP timestamps are not normally aligned to the system clock and start at some random value.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Many operating systems will increment the timestamp for every elapsed millisecond; however, the RFC only states that the ticks should be proportional.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP timestamps are used in an algorithm known as *Protection Against Wrapped Sequence* numbers, or *PAWS*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] PAWS is used when the receive window crosses the sequence number wraparound boundary.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In the case where a packet was potentially retransmitted, it answers the question: "Is this sequence number in the first 4 GB or the second?" And the timestamp is used to break the tie.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Also, the Eifel detection algorithm uses TCP timestamps to determine if retransmissions are occurring because packets are lost or simply out of order.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP timestamps are enabled by default in Linux, and disabled by default in Windows Server 2008, 2012 and 2016.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Recent Statistics show that the level of TCP timestamp adoption has stagnated, at ~40%, owing to Windows Server dropping support since Windows Server 2008.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] It is possible to interrupt or abort the queued stream instead of waiting for the stream to finish.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This is done by specifying the data as *urgent*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This marks the transmission as out-of-band data (OOB) and tells the receiving program to process it immediately.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When finished, TCP informs the application and resumes the stream queue.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An example is when TCP is used for a remote login session where the user can send a keyboard sequence that interrupts or aborts the remotely running program without waiting for the program to finish its current transfer.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The *urgent* pointer only alters the processing on the remote host and doesn't expedite any processing on the network itself.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The capability is implemented differently or poorly on different systems or may not be supported.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Where it is available, it is prudent to assume only single bytes of OOB data will be reliably handled.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Since the feature is not frequently used, it is not well tested on some platforms and has been associated with vulnerabilities, WinNuke for instance.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Normally, TCP waits for 200 ms for a full packet of data to send (Nagle's Algorithm tries to group small messages into a single packet).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This wait creates small, but potentially serious delays if repeated constantly during a file transfer.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] For example, a typical send block would be 4 KB, a typical MSS is 1460, so 2 packets go out on a 10 Mbit/s Ethernet taking ~1.2 ms each followed by a third carrying the remaining 1176 after a 197 ms pause because TCP is waiting for a full buffer.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] In the case of telnet, each user keystroke is echoed back by the server before the user can see it on the screen.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Setting the socket option `TCP_NODELAY` overrides the default 200 ms send delay.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Application programs use this socket option to force output to be sent after writing a character or line of characters.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The RFC 793 defines the `PSH` push bit as "a message to the receiving TCP stack to send this data immediately up to the receiving application".
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] There is no way to indicate or control it in user space using Berkeley sockets; it is controlled by the protocol stack only.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP may be attacked in a variety of ways.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The results of a thorough security assessment of TCP, along with possible mitigations for the identified issues, were published in 2009, and was pursued within the IETF through 2012.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Notable vulnerabilities include denial of service, connection hijacking, TCP veto and TCP reset attack.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] By using a spoofed IP address and repeatedly sending purposely assembled SYN packets, followed by many ACK packets, attackers can cause the server to consume large amounts of resources keeping track of the bogus connections.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Proposed solutions to this problem include SYN cookies and cryptographic puzzles, though SYN cookies come with their own set of vulnerabilities.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Sockstress is a similar attack, that might be mitigated with system resource management.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An advanced DoS attack involving the exploitation of the TCP *persist timer* was analyzed in Phrack No.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An attacker who is able to eavesdrop on a TCP session and redirect packets can hijack a TCP connection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] To do so, the attacker learns the sequence number from the ongoing communication and forges a false segment that looks like the next segment in the stream.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A simple hijack can result in one packet being erroneously accepted at one end.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When the receiving host acknowledges the false segment, synchronization is lost.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Hijacking may be combined with ARP spoofing or other routing attacks that allow an attacker to take permanent control of the TCP connection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Impersonating a different IP address was not difficult prior to RFC 1948 when the initial *sequence number* was easily guessable.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] This is why the initial sequence number is now chosen at random.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] An attacker who can eavesdrop and predict the size of the next packet to be sent can cause the receiver to accept a malicious payload without disrupting the existing connection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The attacker injects a malicious packet with the sequence number and a payload size of the next expected packet.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] When the legitimate packet is ultimately received, it is found to have the same sequence number and length as a packet already received and is silently dropped as a normal duplicate packet—the legitimate packet is *vetoed* by the malicious packet.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Unlike in connection hijacking, the connection is never desynchronized and communication continues as normal after the malicious payload is accepted.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP veto gives the attacker less control over the communication but makes the attack particularly resistant to detection.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The only evidence to the receiver that something is amiss is a single duplicate packet, a normal occurrence in an IP network.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The sender of the vetoed packet never sees any evidence of an attack.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] A TCP connection is identified by a four-tuple of the source address, source port, destination address, and destination port.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Port numbers are used to identify different services, and to allow multiple connections between hosts.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] TCP uses 16-bit port numbers, providing 65,536 possible values for each of the source and destination ports.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The dependency of connection identity on addresses means that TCP connections are bound to a single network path; TCP cannot use other routes that multihomed hosts have available, and connections break if an endpoint's address changes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Port numbers are categorized into three basic categories: well-known, registered, and dynamic or private.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] The well-known ports are assigned by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) and are typically used by system-level processes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Well-known applications running as servers and passively listening for connections typically use these ports.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Registered ports (1024–49151) may be assigned to specific services by third-party developers, but some operating systems also allocate ephemeral client ports from this range.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p01] Dynamic or private ports (49152–65535) are not associated with any registered services and are commonly used exclusively as ephemeral ports for temporary client connections.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] However, while significant enhancements have been made and proposed over the years, its most basic operation has not changed significantly since its first specification RFC 675 in 1974, and the v4 specification RFC 793, published in September 1981.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] RFC 1122, published in October 1989, clarified a number of TCP protocol implementation requirements.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] A list of the 8 required specifications and over 20 strongly encouraged enhancements is available in RFC 7414.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Among this list is RFC 2581, TCP Congestion Control, one of the most important TCP-related RFCs in recent years, describes updated algorithms that avoid undue congestion.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] In 2001, RFC 3168 was written to describe Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN), a congestion avoidance signaling mechanism.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The original TCP congestion avoidance algorithm was known as *TCP Tahoe*, but many alternative algorithms have since been proposed (including TCP Reno, TCP Vegas, FAST TCP, TCP New Reno, and TCP Hybla).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Multipath TCP (MPTCP) is an ongoing effort within the IETF that aims at allowing a TCP connection to use multiple paths to maximize resource usage and increase redundancy.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The redundancy offered by Multipath TCP in the context of wireless networks enables the simultaneous use of different networks, which brings higher throughput and better handover capabilities.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Multipath TCP also brings performance benefits in datacenter environments.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The reference implementation of Multipath TCP was developed in the Linux kernel.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Multipath TCP is used to support the Siri voice recognition application on iPhones, iPads and Macs.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] tcpcrypt is an extension proposed in July 2010 to provide transport-level encryption directly in TCP itself.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] It is designed to work transparently and not require any configuration.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Unlike TLS (SSL), tcpcrypt itself does not provide authentication, but provides simple primitives down to the application to do that.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The tcpcrypt RFC was published by the IETF in May 2019.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP Fast Open is an extension to speed up the opening of successive TCP connections between two endpoints.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] It works by skipping the three-way handshake using a cryptographic *cookie*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] It is similar to an earlier proposal called T/TCP, which was not widely adopted due to security issues.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP Fast Open was published as RFC 7413 in 2014.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Proposed in May 2013, Proportional Rate Reduction (PRR) is a TCP extension developed by Google engineers.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] PRR ensures that the TCP window size after recovery is as close to the slow start threshold as possible.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The algorithm is designed to improve the speed of recovery and is the default congestion control algorithm in Linux 3.2+ kernels.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP Cookie Transactions (TCPCT) is an extension proposed in December 2009 to secure servers against denial-of-service attacks.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Unlike SYN cookies, TCPCT does not conflict with other TCP extensions such as window scaling.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCPCT was designed due to necessities of DNSSEC, where servers have to handle large numbers of short-lived TCP connections.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] In 2016, TCPCT was deprecated in favor of TCP Fast Open.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The status of the original RFC was changed to *historic*.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] One way to overcome the processing power requirements of TCP is to build hardware implementations of it, widely known as TCP offload engines (TOE).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The main problem of TOEs is that they are hard to integrate into computing systems, requiring extensive changes in the operating system of the computer or device.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP low power (*TCPlp*) has been demonstrated to work in resource constrained environments where otherwise UDP-based CoAP is preferred.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The wire data of TCP provides significant information-gathering and modification opportunities to on-path observers, as the protocol metadata is transmitted in cleartext.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] While this transparency is useful to network operators and researchers, information gathered from protocol metadata may reduce the end-user's privacy.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This visibility and malleability of metadata has led to TCP being difficult to extend—a case of protocol ossification—as any intermediate node (a 'middlebox') can make decisions based on that metadata or even modify it, breaking the end-to-end principle.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] One measurement found that a third of paths across the Internet encounter at least one intermediary that modifies TCP metadata, and 6.5% of paths encounter harmful ossifying effects from intermediaries.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Avoiding extensibility hazards from intermediaries placed significant constraints on the design of MPTCP, and difficulties caused by intermediaries have hindered the deployment of TCP Fast Open in web browsers.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Another source of ossification is the difficulty of modification of TCP functions at the endpoints, typically in the operating system kernel or in hardware with a TCP offload engine.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] If multiple independent higher-level messages are encapsulated and multiplexed onto a single TCP connection, then head-of-line blocking can cause processing of a fully-received message that was sent later to wait for delivery of a message that was sent earlier.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Web browsers attempt to mitigate head-of-line blocking by opening multiple parallel connections.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This incurs the cost of connection establishment repeatedly, as well as multiplying the resources needed to track those connections at the endpoints.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Connection establishment is a major contributor to latency as experienced by web users.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP's three-way handshake introduces one RTT of latency during connection establishment before data can be sent.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] For short flows, these delays are very significant.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Transport Layer Security (TLS) requires a handshake of its own for key exchange at connection establishment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Because of the layered design, the TCP handshake and the TLS handshake proceed serially; the TLS handshake cannot begin until the TCP handshake has concluded.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Two RTTs are required for connection establishment with TLS 1.2 over TCP.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP Fast Open allows the transmission of data in the initial (i.e., SYN and SYN-ACK) packets, removing one RTT of latency during connection establishment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] However, TCP Fast Open has been difficult to deploy due to protocol ossification; as of 2020, no Web browsers used it by default.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP throughput is affected by packet reordering.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Reordered packets can cause duplicate acknowledgments to be sent, which, if they cross a threshold, will then trigger a spurious retransmission and congestion control.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Transmission behavior can also become bursty, as large ranges are acknowledged all at once when a reordered packet at the range's start is received (in a manner similar to how head-of-line blocking affects applications).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Blanton & Allman (2002) found that throughput was inversely related to the amount of reordering, up to a threshold where all reordering triggers spurious retransmission.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Mitigating reordering depends on a sender's ability to determine that it has sent a spurious retransmission, and hence on resolving retransmission ambiguity.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Reducing reordering-induced spurious retransmissions may slow recovery from genuine loss.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Selective acknowledgment can provide a significant benefit to throughput; Bruyeron, Hemon & Zhang (1998) measured gains of up to 45%.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] An important factor in the improvement is that selective acknowledgment can more often avoid going into slow start after a loss and can hence better use available bandwidth.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] However, TCP can only selectively acknowledge a maximum of three blocks of sequence numbers.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This can limit the retransmission rate and hence loss recovery or cause needless retransmissions, especially in high-loss environments.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] TCP was originally designed for wired networks where packet loss is considered to be the result of network congestion and the congestion window size is reduced dramatically as a precaution.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] However, wireless links are known to experience sporadic and usually temporary losses due to fading, shadowing, hand off, interference, and other radio effects, that are not strictly congestion.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] After the (erroneous) back-off of the congestion window size, due to wireless packet loss, there may be a congestion avoidance phase with a conservative decrease in window size.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This causes the radio link to be underused.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Extensive research on combating these harmful effects has been conducted.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Suggested solutions can be categorized as end-to-end solutions, which require modifications at the client or server, link layer solutions, such as Radio Link Protocol in cellular networks, or proxy-based solutions which require some changes in the network without modifying end nodes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] A number of alternative congestion control algorithms, such as Vegas, Westwood, Veno, and Santa Cruz, have been proposed to help solve the wireless problem.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The idea of a TCP accelerator is to terminate TCP connections inside the network processor and then relay the data to a second connection toward the end system.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The data packets that originate from the sender are buffered at the accelerator node, which is responsible for performing local retransmissions in the event of packet loss.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Thus, in case of losses, the feedback loop between the sender and the receiver is shortened to the one between the acceleration node and the receiver which guarantees a faster delivery of data to the receiver.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Since TCP is a rate-adaptive protocol, the rate at which the TCP sender injects packets into the network is directly proportional to the prevailing load condition within the network as well as the processing capacity of the receiver.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The prevalent conditions within the network are judged by the sender on the basis of the acknowledgments received by it.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The acceleration node splits the feedback loop between the sender and the receiver and thus guarantees a shorter round trip time (RTT) per packet.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] A shorter RTT is beneficial as it ensures a quicker response time to any changes in the network and a faster adaptation by the sender to combat these changes.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Disadvantages of the method include the fact that the TCP session has to be directed through the accelerator; this means that if routing changes so that the accelerator is no longer in the path, the connection will be broken.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] It also destroys the end-to-end property of the TCP ACK mechanism; when the ACK is received by the sender, the packet has been stored by the accelerator, not delivered to the receiver.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] A packet sniffer, which taps TCP traffic on a network link, can be useful in debugging networks, network stacks, and applications that use TCP by showing an engineer what packets are passing through a link.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Some networking stacks support the SO_DEBUG socket option, which can be enabled on the socket using setsockopt.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] That option dumps all the packets, TCP states, and events on that socket, which is helpful in debugging.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Netstat is another utility that can be used for debugging.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] For many applications TCP is not appropriate.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The application cannot normally access the packets coming after a lost packet until the retransmitted copy of the lost packet is received.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This causes problems for real-time applications such as streaming media, real-time multiplayer games and voice over IP (VoIP) where it is generally more useful to get most of the data in a timely fashion than it is to get all of the data in order.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] For historical and performance reasons, most storage area networks (SANs) use Fibre Channel Protocol (FCP) over Fibre Channel connections.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] For embedded systems, network booting, and servers that serve simple requests from huge numbers of clients (e.g.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] DNS servers) the complexity of TCP can be a problem.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Tricks such as transmitting data between two hosts that are both behind NAT (using STUN or similar systems) are far simpler without a relatively complex protocol like TCP in the way.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Generally, where TCP is unsuitable, the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) is used.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) is another protocol that provides reliable stream-oriented services similar to TCP.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] It is newer and considerably more complex than TCP, and has not yet seen widespread deployment.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] However, it is especially designed to be used in situations where reliability and near-real-time considerations are important.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Venturi Transport Protocol (VTP) is a patented proprietary protocol that is designed to replace TCP transparently to overcome perceived inefficiencies related to wireless data transport.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Especially in mobile communications and wireless networks, data transmission may become unstable due to high latency and signal interference.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The TCP congestion avoidance algorithm works very well for ad-hoc environments where the data sender is not known in advance.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] If the environment is predictable, a timing-based protocol such as Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) can avoid TCP's retransmission overhead.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] UDP-based Data Transfer Protocol (UDT) is designed for high-bandwidth, high-latency network environments, particularly for large-scale data transfers such as file or media streaming.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] In networks with a high bandwidth-delay product, UDT offers advantages over TCP, providing better efficiency and fairness.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Multipurpose Transaction Protocol (MTP/IP) is patented proprietary software that is designed to adaptively achieve high throughput and transaction performance in a wide variety of network conditions, particularly those where TCP is perceived to be inefficient.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] In other words, after appropriate padding, all 16-bit words are added using ones' complement arithmetic.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The sum is then bitwise complemented and inserted as the checksum field.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] The length of the TCP header and data (measured in octets).
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] A pseudo-header that mimics the IPv6 header for computation of the checksum is shown below.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] Many TCP/IP software stack implementations provide options to use hardware assistance to automatically compute the checksum in the network adapter prior to transmission onto the network or upon reception from the network for validation.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This may reduce CPU load associated with calculating the checksum, potentially increasing overall network performance.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This feature may cause packet analyzers that are unaware or uncertain about the use of checksum offload to report invalid checksums in outbound packets that have not yet reached the network adapter.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This will only occur for packets that are intercepted before being transmitted by the network adapter; all packets transmitted by the network adaptor on the wire will have valid checksums.
[src:game-networking/transmission-control-protocol-p02] This issue can also occur when monitoring packets being transmitted between virtual machines on the same host, where a virtual device driver may omit the checksum calculation (as an optimization), knowing that the checksum will be calculated later by the VM host kernel or its physical hardware.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In computer networking, the **User Datagram Protocol** (**UDP**) is one of the core communication protocols of the Internet protocol suite used to send messages (transported as datagrams in packets) to other hosts on an Internet Protocol (IP) network.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Within an IP network, UDP does not require prior communication to set up communication channels or data paths.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] UDP is a connectionless protocol, meaning that messages are sent without negotiating a connection and that UDP does not keep track of what it has sent.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] UDP provides checksums for data integrity, and port numbers for addressing different functions at the source and destination of the datagram.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] It has no handshaking dialogues and thus exposes the user's program to any unreliability of the underlying network; there is no guarantee of delivery, ordering, or duplicate protection.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If error-correction facilities are needed at the network interface level, an application may instead use Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP), which are designed for this purpose.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] UDP is suitable for purposes where error checking and correction are either not necessary or are performed in the application; UDP avoids the overhead of such processing in the protocol stack.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Time-sensitive applications often use UDP because dropping packets is preferable to waiting for packets delayed due to retransmission, which may not be an option in a real-time system.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Reed in 1980 and formally defined in RFC 768.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] UDP is a simple message-oriented transport layer protocol that is documented in RFC 768.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Although UDP provides integrity verification (via checksum) of the header and payload, it provides no guarantees to the upper layer protocol for message delivery and the UDP layer retains no state of UDP messages once sent.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] For this reason, UDP sometimes is referred to as *Unreliable Datagram Protocol*.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If transmission reliability is desired, it must be implemented in the user's application.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] A number of UDP's attributes make it especially suited for certain applications.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Applications can use datagram sockets to establish host-to-host communications.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] An application binds a socket to its endpoint of data transmission, which is a combination of an IP address and a port.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In this way, UDP provides application multiplexing.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] A port is a software structure that is identified by the port number, a 16-bit integer value, allowing for port numbers between 0 and 65535.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Port 0 is reserved, but is a permissible source port value if the sending process does not expect messages in response.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) has divided port numbers into three ranges.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Port numbers 0 through 1023 are used for common, well-known services.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] On Unix-like operating systems, using one of these ports requires superuser operating permission.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Port numbers 1024 through 49151 are the registered ports used for IANA-registered services.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Ports 49152 through 65535 are dynamic ports that are not officially designated for any specific service and may be used for any purpose.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] These may also be used as ephemeral ports, which software running on the host may use to dynamically create communications endpoints as needed.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] A UDP datagram consists of a datagram *header* followed by a *data* section (the payload data for the application).
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The use of the *Checksum* and *Source Port* fields is optional in IPv4 (light purple background in table).
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In IPv6, only the *Source Port* field is optional.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If not used, these fields should be set to zero.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] This field identifies the sender's port, when used, and should be assumed to be the port to reply to if needed.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If the source host is the client, the port number is likely to be an ephemeral port.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] This field identifies the receiver's port and is required.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Similar to the source port number, if the client is the destination host then the port number will likely be an ephemeral port number, and if the destination host is the server, then the port number will likely be a well-known port number.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The minimum length is 8 bytes, the length of the header.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The field size sets a theoretical limit of 65,535 bytes (8-byte header + 65,527 bytes of data) for a UDP datagram.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] it is possible to have UDP datagrams of size greater than 65,535 bytes.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The length field is set to zero if the length of the UDP header plus UDP data is greater than 65,535.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The checksum field may be used for error-checking of the header and data.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] This field is optional in IPv4, and mandatory in most cases in IPv6.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In other words, all 16-bit words are summed using ones' complement arithmetic.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] On each addition, if a carry-out (17th bit) is produced, swing that 17th carry bit around and add it to the least significant bit of the running total.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Finally, the sum is then ones' complemented to yield the value of the UDP checksum field.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If the checksum calculation results in the value zero (all 16 bits 0) it should be sent as the ones' complement (all 1s) as a zero-value checksum indicates no checksum has been calculated.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In this case, any specific processing is not required at the receiver, because all 0s and all 1s are equal to zero in 1's complement arithmetic.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The differences between IPv4 and IPv6 are in the pseudo header used to compute the checksum, and that the checksum is not optional in IPv6.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Under specific conditions, a UDP application using IPv6 is allowed to use a zero UDP zero-checksum mode with a tunnel protocol.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] When UDP runs over IPv4, the checksum is computed using a *pseudo header* that contains some of the same information from the real IPv4 header.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The pseudo header is not the real IPv4 header used to send an IP packet, it is used only for the checksum calculation.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] UDP checksum computation is optional for IPv4.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If a checksum is not used, it should be set to the value zero.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The source address from the IPv4 header.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The destination address from the IPv4 header.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The length of the UDP header and data (measured in octets).
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Lacking reliability, UDP applications may encounter some packet loss, reordering, errors or duplication.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] If using UDP, the end-user applications must provide any necessary handshaking, such as real-time confirmation that the message has been received.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Certain applications (e.g., TFTP) may incorporate rudimentary reliability mechanisms at the application layer as required.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] For applications demanding a high degree of reliability, an alternative protocol such as the Transmission Control Protocol may be used instead.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Most often, UDP applications do not employ reliability mechanisms and may even be hindered by them.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Streaming media, real-time multiplayer games and voice over IP (VoIP) are typical applications that leverage UDP.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In these particular applications, loss of packets is not usually a fatal problem.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] In VoIP, for example, latency and jitter are the primary concerns.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] The use of TCP would cause jitter if any packets were lost, as TCP does not provide subsequent data to the application while it is requesting a re-send of the missing data.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Numerous key Internet applications use UDP, including: the Domain Name System (DNS), the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP), the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Voice and video traffic is generally transmitted using UDP.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Real-time video and audio streaming protocols are designed to handle the occasional lost packets, so only slight degradation in quality occurs, compared to the large delays that would occur if lost packets were retransmitted.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Some VPN systems, such as OpenVPN, support operation over UDP and provide application-layer error checking as well as mechanisms to enhance transmission reliability.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] WireGuard uses UDP and performs error checking, but does not provide any reliability guarantees; reliability is delegated to upper-layer protocols within the tunnel or to end applications.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] QUIC is a transport protocol built on top of UDP.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] QUIC provides a reliable and secure connection.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC as opposed to earlier versions of HTTPS which use a combination of TCP and TLS to ensure reliability and security respectively.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] This means that HTTP/3 uses a single handshake to set up a connection, rather than having two separate handshakes for TCP and TLS, meaning the overall time to establish a connection is reduced.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Transmission Control Protocol is a connection-oriented protocol and requires handshaking to set up end-to-end communications.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Once a connection is set up, user data may be sent bi-directionally over the connection.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] User Datagram Protocol is a simpler message-based connectionless protocol.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Connectionless protocols do not set up a dedicated end-to-end connection.
[src:game-networking/user-datagram-protocol] Communication is achieved by transmitting information in one direction from source to destination without verifying the readiness or state of the receiver.
